WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:16.800
The mobile systems are mobile devices.

00:16.800 --> 00:17.800
What are mobile devices?

00:17.800 --> 00:33.800
Well, it's all of our devices.

00:33.800 --> 00:36.800
Mobile systems are mobile devices.

00:36.800 --> 00:37.800
What are mobile devices?

00:37.800 --> 00:40.800
Well, it's all of our devices that are mobile.

00:40.800 --> 00:45.800
Things like our iPhones, our iPads, our little mini-super computers

00:45.800 --> 00:50.800
that we keep in our pockets that store gigabytes, maybe even terabytes of data

00:50.800 --> 00:54.800
and are unbelievably powerful little computers.

00:54.800 --> 00:56.800
So what's the risk with these mobile devices?

00:56.800 --> 01:00.800
Well, it's the fact that they can store so much data nowadays

01:00.800 --> 01:02.800
and the fact that they're mobile.

01:02.800 --> 01:05.800
Because what inevitably happens is someone puts a bunch of data on this device

01:05.800 --> 01:07.800
that probably shouldn't be on there.

01:07.800 --> 01:11.800
And then they forget their device somewhere inevitably in the cab,

01:11.800 --> 01:13.800
in the airport, on the train.

01:13.800 --> 01:16.800
Let's talk about an example of this actually occurring.

01:16.800 --> 01:20.800
And it highlights just what the risks are with mobile devices.

01:20.800 --> 01:26.800
So there was a healthcare provider in the US, I think it was in Minnesota, in 2011.

01:26.800 --> 01:31.800
A employee of that company left their laptop in their car.

01:31.800 --> 01:36.800
The laptop had about 20 million records on it, on about 23,000 patients.

01:36.800 --> 01:41.800
And they left this laptop in their car when they wanted to do a Starbucks or something like that.

01:41.800 --> 01:45.800
And what inevitably happens, the laptop was stolen.

01:45.800 --> 01:50.800
There was a whole series of extremely unfortunate events that all occurred

01:50.800 --> 01:53.800
because of that lost one lost laptop.

01:53.800 --> 01:55.800
So what happened?

01:55.800 --> 01:57.800
Well, there was a lawsuit by the Auditor General.

01:57.800 --> 02:01.800
There was a giant settlement, millions of dollars with the Auditor General.

02:01.800 --> 02:05.800
Their CEO, COO, CFO were all fired and replaced.

02:05.800 --> 02:10.800
There was two class action lawsuits from patients whose data was potentially exposed.

02:10.800 --> 02:14.800
There was a settlement with the FTC.

02:14.800 --> 02:16.800
Over 170 jobs were cut.

02:16.800 --> 02:20.800
And as a final kick in the pants, they were delisted from the New York Stock Exchange.

02:20.800 --> 02:22.800
They were publicly traded company.

02:22.800 --> 02:28.800
All of this, all of these tragic events occurred because of one lost laptop.

02:28.800 --> 02:30.800
And then companies never recovered.

02:30.800 --> 02:32.800
I've checked on their stock price a couple times since then.

02:32.800 --> 02:33.800
And they've never recovered.

02:33.800 --> 02:35.800
They've never gotten back to the highs they were once at.

02:35.800 --> 02:37.800
And they don't actually exist anymore.

02:37.800 --> 02:38.800
They were bought out.

02:38.800 --> 02:44.800
So this whole tale of woe was because of one lost or stolen laptop.

02:44.800 --> 02:46.800
So let's spend a minute thinking about this.

02:46.800 --> 02:50.800
What would be the best way to have prevented this event from occurring?

02:50.800 --> 02:52.800
This lost or stolen laptop?

02:52.800 --> 02:55.800
And all the horrible things that happened afterwards?

02:55.800 --> 02:57.800
About a lot of you were thinking, hold drive encryption.

02:57.800 --> 03:01.800
They should have encrypted the entire contents of the hard drive.

03:01.800 --> 03:06.800
Because the whole idea behind hold drive encryption is, even if someone steals your laptop,

03:06.800 --> 03:09.800
they'll find that all the data is being encrypted.

03:09.800 --> 03:13.800
And don't get me wrong, hold drive encryption, excellent idea, defense and depth,

03:13.800 --> 03:16.800
have multiple layers of controls, all good.

03:16.800 --> 03:20.800
But there's actually more of a flaw in hold drive encryption than most people realize.

03:20.800 --> 03:25.800
And that is, while the hold drive encryption is amazing, it'll use, you know, like AES,

03:25.800 --> 03:30.800
256-based encryption, it's unbelievably difficult to break the encryption.

03:30.800 --> 03:34.800
But the problem is, if someone has stolen your laptop,

03:34.800 --> 03:38.800
how long do they have to figure out how to break that encryption?

03:38.800 --> 03:43.800
And do they, in fact, need that extremely difficult to find 256-bit key?

03:43.800 --> 03:44.800
No.

03:44.800 --> 03:50.800
What they, in fact, need to unlock that excellent encryption is the user's password.

03:50.800 --> 03:53.800
And how good are our user's passwords?

03:53.800 --> 03:54.800
Horrible.

03:54.800 --> 03:57.800
The most common password in the world is password.

03:57.800 --> 04:01.800
So an attacker that steals a laptop that has hold drive encryption

04:01.800 --> 04:06.800
has an unlimited amount of time to try and discover probably a very bad password.

04:06.800 --> 04:10.800
And you might be saying, oh, but lots of laptops have protection mechanisms that only allow you

04:10.800 --> 04:12.800
to try a password so many times.

04:12.800 --> 04:17.800
Well, those mechanisms are pretty easy to defeat if you have physical control of a laptop

04:17.800 --> 04:18.800
of its in your possession.

04:18.800 --> 04:23.800
So hold drive encryption, not a bad control, but not the best way for preventing this.

04:23.800 --> 04:24.800
Okay.

04:24.800 --> 04:28.800
What about remote white capabilities?

04:28.800 --> 04:33.800
Lots of cell phones and even some laptops have the ability to remotely wipe the device.

04:33.800 --> 04:38.800
Again, not a bad control, but not as good as most people think.

04:38.800 --> 04:43.800
Because what's required for that remote white capability to be activated?

04:43.800 --> 04:48.800
The device has to be sent a signal and the device has to receive that signal.

04:48.800 --> 04:49.800
And he's skilled attacker.

04:49.800 --> 04:52.800
Soon as they steal a laptop, what are they going to do?

04:52.800 --> 04:55.800
Well, they're going to put that laptop in a fair day cage,

04:55.800 --> 04:59.800
in an envelope in something that's going to block that signal from being received.

04:59.800 --> 05:02.800
And then when they get it back to their criminal layer and their parents' basement,

05:02.800 --> 05:05.800
they're going to put themselves in this fair day cage.

05:05.800 --> 05:12.800
And so that laptop, is it ever going to receive that kill switch that signal to wipe the drive?

05:12.800 --> 05:13.800
Of course not.

05:13.800 --> 05:17.800
Now, for reasons, I decided to look into this a little bit.

05:17.800 --> 05:20.800
I thought, you know, let's find out how expensive it is to get one of these sleeves

05:20.800 --> 05:23.800
that you can put a laptop in a fair day cage, essentially.

05:23.800 --> 05:28.800
So I went on Amazon and on Amazon.com, like 2030 bucks, you can get a nice haul quality one.

05:28.800 --> 05:30.800
I was like, that's pretty good, not too bad.

05:30.800 --> 05:32.800
Then I was like, I bet you can do better.

05:32.800 --> 05:35.800
So I went to Alibaba, straight from China, right?

05:35.800 --> 05:38.800
On Alibaba, as long as you're willing to buy like 500 of them,

05:38.800 --> 05:40.800
you get them for like three bucks a piece.

05:40.800 --> 05:41.800
Pretty darn good.

05:41.800 --> 05:44.800
But then I thought, you know what? I can do even better.

05:44.800 --> 05:46.800
So it turns out, bag of chips.

05:46.800 --> 05:50.800
If you open up a bag of chips, you see that silver lining inside, it's mylar.

05:50.800 --> 05:52.800
It's a pretty good blocker of radio waves.

05:53.800 --> 05:57.800
So you go to Costco, buy yourselves a jumbo bag of chips, you got snacks,

05:57.800 --> 06:00.800
you got the fair day cage you need, there you go.

06:00.800 --> 06:03.800
You can defeat the remote wipe capability.

06:03.800 --> 06:08.800
So what's the best answer for how we prevent this type of mobile data breach?

06:08.800 --> 06:13.800
The best answer in fact is to not have the data on the laptop.

06:13.800 --> 06:18.800
If there isn't sensitive data on the laptop, then there's no worries about that laptop being lost or stolen,

06:18.800 --> 06:21.800
which is inevitably going to happen.

06:21.800 --> 06:26.800
So it turns out, one of the best ways of preventing these types of breaches is policies,

06:26.800 --> 06:29.800
procedures, user awareness training, and education,

06:29.800 --> 06:34.800
so that users know not to store highly sensitive data on their mobile devices.

06:34.800 --> 06:39.800
So when we think about how do we reduce the risk of mobile devices,

06:39.800 --> 06:42.800
one of the best ways is through policy, education, awareness.

06:42.800 --> 06:46.800
And then of course, do have the other physically and the other controls in place,

06:46.800 --> 06:49.800
still a very good idea, defense and depth to have things like whole drive encryption,

06:49.800 --> 06:54.800
to have remote wipe capabilities, to have good anti-malware capabilities, whatever.

06:54.800 --> 06:58.800
You know, still use all those controls, but the best one, training and awareness.

06:58.800 --> 07:03.800
Now let's talk about a couple of other controls that are really important to have with mobile devices.

07:03.800 --> 07:08.800
And we'll get into how you secure the connection between mobile device and the device itself at a moment.

07:08.800 --> 07:13.800
But one other thing we should spend a moment on here is if you're writing an application

07:13.800 --> 07:16.800
that's going to be used on a mobile device, which is very common nowadays,

07:16.800 --> 07:21.800
writing apps and web apps for phones and laptops and things like that.

07:21.800 --> 07:24.800
There's a really good set of guidance out there.

07:24.800 --> 07:30.800
A top 10 list of the top 10 things you should probably avoid when you're creating your mobile application.

07:30.800 --> 07:33.800
So there's an organization out there that probably many of you have heard of,

07:33.800 --> 07:38.800
a WASP. They do a really great job of investigating mobile devices,

07:38.800 --> 07:42.800
web applications, things like that, and figuring out what are the top 10 security risks

07:42.800 --> 07:47.800
that cause the vast majority of the breaches. And they've created a mobile device top 10,

07:47.800 --> 07:53.800
and it's listed here on the screen. Don't need to memorize it, but do know what you could use something like this for.

07:53.800 --> 07:59.800
And the use of something like this is if you're developing an application or a group within your organization

07:59.800 --> 08:04.800
is developing an application, they should be very aware of things like the OOS mobile top 10.

08:04.800 --> 08:11.800
And they should be making sure that the application they're creating is not vulnerable to any of these top 10 things.

08:11.800 --> 08:17.800
Continuing on the concept of policies related to mobile devices.

08:17.800 --> 08:22.800
A couple of major policies you should have related to mobile devices are things like an acceptable use policy.

08:22.800 --> 08:29.800
What mobile devices can and can't be used for? For organizations that allow employees to bring in their own devices,

08:29.800 --> 08:33.800
their own phones, you should have things like BYOD or CYOD policies.

08:33.800 --> 08:37.800
Bring your own device. I always think it's BYOD, bring your own booths, but that's totally different thing.

08:37.800 --> 08:45.800
So BYOD is bring your own device, CYOD carry your own device. These are policies that define if someone's bringing in their own personal device,

08:45.800 --> 08:49.800
requiring, for instance, certain security controls be there from a corporate perspective,

08:49.800 --> 08:53.800
making sure the phones aren't jail-broken, that they have a whole drive encryption, that sort of thing.

08:53.800 --> 08:57.800
And it's also a good idea to have a policy around personal computers.

08:57.800 --> 09:06.800
And in my opinion that policy should be, no personal computers allowed, it's very, very difficult for an organization to know that a personal computer is secure.

09:07.800 --> 09:18.800
There's so many ways to install, backdoor is an unintended, you know, things on a laptop that a corporation does not want to bring into their environment.

09:18.800 --> 09:25.800
Now when we think about mobile devices, the whole point of having a mobile device is you can use it wherever you are anywhere in the world.

09:25.800 --> 09:29.800
And often we are connecting that mobile device back to our corporate network.

09:29.800 --> 09:34.800
And we're transferring data back and forth between wherever we are in the world and the corporate network.

09:34.800 --> 09:41.800
And where is that data transiting? The internet. The biggest hive of vile scum in the world, right?

09:41.800 --> 09:48.800
I mean, it's the internet. No traffic going around across the internet should be secure traffic, unless that traffic is encrypted.

09:48.800 --> 09:55.800
So an important security control to have with mobile devices is to encrypt the traffic between the mobile device and the corporate network.

09:55.800 --> 10:00.800
And while we often use for this, our solutions like VPNs, virtual private networks.

10:00.800 --> 10:03.800
And we'll talk about VPNs in a lot more detail in the networking domain.

10:03.800 --> 10:10.800
The final consideration is the security of the endpoint itself, even if you have the most secure connection in the world.

10:10.800 --> 10:19.800
An attacker is still going to know all the sensitive data if they have control of the endpoint if they've somehow installed a backdoor or malware on the phone or the laptop.

10:19.800 --> 10:28.800
So the final major piece of mobile security is how do you actually make sure that the endpoint that the laptop, iPad, phone is actually secure.

10:28.800 --> 10:36.800
And that's that we use that concept of hardening, right, where you go through whatever the appropriate security controls are to disable on an unnecessary services,

10:36.800 --> 10:40.800
close unneeded ports, install anti malware, all those sorts of things.

10:40.800 --> 10:44.800
And you should do that for any of your mobile devices that you're using out there.

